 two approaches for handling unused parameters:

  Two Approaches for Unused Stub Parameters

  Approach 1: Prefix with Underscore (_param)

  What it does: Rename the parameter to start with _ to indicate "intentionally unused"

  # Before (ARG002 warning)
  async def get_query_suggestions(self, partial_query: str) -> Any:
      """Get suggestions for completing a partial query."""
      return Result.fail(Errors.system(
          message="Query suggestions not yet implemented",
          operation="get_query_suggestions"
      ))

  # After (No warning - underscore indicates intentional)
  async def get_query_suggestions(self, _partial_query: str) -> Any:
      """Get suggestions for completing a partial query."""
      return Result.fail(Errors.system(
          message="Query suggestions not yet implemented",
          operation="get_query_suggestions"
      ))

  Effect:
  - ✅ Convention-based - Python convention for "I know this is unused"
  - ✅ Self-documenting - Clear signal to readers
  - ✅ Preserves signature - Still has the parameter in the signature
  - ⚠ Callers must use keyword - obj.method(_partial_query="foo") looks weird
  - ⚠ Changes public API - If this is a public method, parameter name matters

  ---
  Approach 2: Type Ignore Comment (# type: ignore[ARG002])

  What it does: Suppress the specific linting rule for that line

  # Before (ARG002 warning)
  async def get_query_suggestions(self, partial_query: str) -> Any:

  # After (Warning suppressed)
  async def get_query_suggestions(self, partial_query: str) -> Any:  # type: ignore[ARG002]
      """Get suggestions for completing a partial query."""

  Or on the parameter itself:
  async def get_query_suggestions(
      self,
      partial_query: str  # type: ignore[ARG002]
  ) -> Any:
      """Get suggestions for completing a partial query."""

  Effect:
  - ✅ Preserves API - Parameter name unchanged
  - ✅ Explicit suppression - Clear that we're ignoring the rule
  - ✅ Callers unaffected - obj.method(partial_query="foo") works normally
  - ⚠ Less obvious - Reader might not notice the comment
  - ⚠ Tool-specific - Relies on linter understanding the comment

  ---
  Comparison Table

  | Aspect                | _parameter               | # type: ignore[ARG002]     |
  |-----------------------|--------------------------|----------------------------|
  | Public API Impact     | ❌ Changes parameter name | ✅ Preserves parameter name |
  | Self-Documenting      | ✅ Very clear to humans   | ⚠ Easy to miss            |
  | Convention            | ✅ Pythonic convention    | ⚠ Tool-specific           |
  | Caller Experience     | ❌ Weird keyword args     | ✅ Normal usage             |
  | Future Implementation | ⚠ Must rename back      | ✅ Just remove comment      |
  | Type Checking         | ✅ Works everywhere       | ⚠ Mypy/Ruff specific      |

  ---
  My Recommendation for SKUEL

  For stub methods in neo4j_adapter.py, I recommend:

  Use _parameter prefix for these reasons:

  1. These are implementation details - neo4j_adapter.py is an adapter, not a public API
  2. Clear intent - Makes it obvious the method is a stub
  3. No API contract - Internal methods can have parameter names changed
  4. Pythonic - Matches Python conventions

